  "slug": "anglicised-dhansak",
  "title": "Anglicised dhansak",
  "subtitle": "Lamb, lentil, and squash curry with tamarind",
  "excerpt": "Lamb shoulder braised with red lentils, butternut squash, and tomato in a spiced onion base, soured with tamarind. The Anglo-Indian adaptation of the Parsi dhansak, richer and milder than the original, but keeping its defining combination of meat, lentil, and sweet-sour finish.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Based on the Parsi dhansak tradition as adapted through Anglo-Indian cooking, documented in Niloufer Ichaporia King, 'My Bombay Kitchen' (2007) and Lizzie Collingham, 'Curry: A Tale of Cooks and Conquerors' (2005). The Parsi original uses a specific blend of dhansak masala; this version uses curry powder and garam masala as practical substitutes for the Anglo-Indian kitchen.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Dhansak is a Parsi dish from western India that came into Anglo-Indian cooking as a special-occasion curry. Meat braises slowly with lentils and vegetables until they melt together. Tamarind sharpens the lot at the end. The full Parsi version uses up to four types of lentil and its own spice blend. This easier version uses red lentils and house curry powder. Less depth, same shape.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The tamarind is the flavour that distinguishes dhansak from other lentil curries. Use tamarind paste rather than tamarind concentrate, the paste has more complexity. It goes in near the end and should be tasted carefully: the right amount of sourness is personal, but the dish should have a clear sweet-sour finish.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
