          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Brown the lamb and build the base",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat {{sunflower-oil}} of oil in a Dutch oven over a high heat. Brown {{lamb-shoulder}} of lamb shoulder in batches and set aside. Reduce the heat to medium, add {{onion}} sliced onion, and cook for 10 minutes until golden. Add {{garlic}} garlic, {{ginger-fresh}} ginger, {{curry-powder}} of curry powder, and {{turmeric-ground}} of turmeric. Stir for 2 minutes.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Braise with lentils and squash",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Return the lamb to the pot. Add {{tinned-tomatoes}} of tinned tomatoes, {{red-lentils}} of rinsed lentils, {{butternut-squash}} of squash, and {{stock-chicken}} of chicken stock. Season with {{sea-salt-fine}} of salt. Bring to the boil, cover, and simmer on a low heat for 60 to 70 minutes until the lamb is tender and the lentils have dissolved into the sauce. Add {{tamarind-paste}} of tamarind paste, stir, and taste, add more if you want more sourness. Stir in {{garam-masala}} of garam masala, rest for 10 minutes, and scatter {{coriander-fresh}} fresh coriander to serve.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
