      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Dhansak is Parsi food first. In western India it is eaten at family celebrations, always with brown rice and caramelised onions. It came to British tables in the colonial period through Bombay's Parsi cooks. In curry houses it sits between rogan josh and balti: a richer dish with the body of the lentils. The home version is the proper one. Restaurant versions rarely come close.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
